<subSubSection pageId="44" pageNumber="45" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="44.[151,1437,151,933]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,799,824]" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">Etymology.</emphasis>
From the Latin adjective, “ 
<taxonomicName box="[641,730,800,824]" class="Insecta" family="Tachinidae" genus="Houghia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="confinis">
<emphasis box="[641,730,800,824]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="45">confinis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
”, meaning adjacent, in reference to the convergence of the pair of dark stripes on each side of the scutum that unite or converge toward one another at the level of the third postsutural dorsocentral seta.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
